---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---
<BaseLayout title="Research" description="Ongoing questions, experiments, and reading trails by Koh Tze Rui." current="research">
  <main>
    <header class="page-head wrap reveal">
      <p class="eyebrow">Research / Questions in motion</p>
      <h1>What I'm<br /><em>looking into.</em></h1>
      <p>Ongoing inquiries, experiments, and reading trails. These are living questions rather than polished answers.</p>
    </header>

    <section class="identity-map wrap reveal" aria-label="Research identity map">
      <div>
        <p class="eyebrow">Research map / Core interests</p>
        <h2>Where my interests overlap.</h2>
        <p>My current centre of gravity sits between Artificial Intelligence, High Performance Computing, and Concurrency: understanding intelligent systems, making them fast, and reasoning about work that happens in parallel.</p>
      </div>
      <figure class="identity-mark">
        <img src="/images/brand/research-venn-symbol-transparent.png" alt="Venn diagram logo showing Artificial Intelligence, High Performance Computing, and Concurrency as overlapping circles." loading="lazy" />
      </figure>
    </section>

    <section class="project-list wrap">
      <article class="project"><span class="project-num">01</span><div><h2>Visual explanations for AI systems</h2><p>How might spatial notes, diagrams, and progressive disclosure help technical readers reason about model behaviour?</p></div><span class="project-type">Active - Human-AI</span><span>-&gt;</span></article>
      <article class="project"><span class="project-num">02</span><div><h2>High Performance Computing for AI</h2><p>Understanding how systems choices, memory movement, kernels, and parallelism shape the speed of model inference.</p></div><span class="project-type">Reading trail - HPC</span><span>-&gt;</span></article>
      <article class="project"><span class="project-num">03</span><div><h2>Interfaces as learning environments</h2><p>Exploring how explanations and tooling can teach mental models without turning into instruction manuals.</p></div><span class="project-type">Writing - Design</span><span>-&gt;</span></article>
    </section>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>